  "type": "mcq",
  "title": "How energy levels indicate absorption",
  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of 6 energy levels. The lines are labeled as followed, starting at the bottom and moving upward. Line 1: Energy, negative 6.22 electron-volts, n equals 1. Line 2: Energy, negative 2.55 electron-volts, n equals 2. Energy, negative 1.51 electron-volts, n equals 3. Line 4: Energy, negative 0.85 electron-volts, n equals 4. Line 5: Energy, 0.54 electron-volts, n equals 5. Line 6: Energy, 0, n equals infinity.\" height=\"230\" src=\"/images/99549a83ef854628b553416788dd981b.png\" width=\"244\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The figure shows some of the energy levels for a hypothetical atom. A photon of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"487 nanometers\"><math alttext=\"487 nanometers\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>487</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>nm</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has an energy of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2.55 electron-volts\"><math alttext=\"2.55 electron-volts\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>2.55</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Which of the following correctly indicates whether the absorption spectrum of a collection of these atoms will have a dark line at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"487 nanometers\"><math alttext=\"487 nanometers\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>487</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>nm</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and describes a feature of the model that indicates this? (The absorption spectrum does not include any process that ionizes the atom.)</p>\n",
    "answer": "i3",
    "choices": [
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes. The atom has energy levels that have magnitudes less than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2.55 electron-volts\"><math alttext=\"2.55 electron-volts\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>2.55</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>",
        "value": "i1"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes. The atom has an energy level that is exactly the same energy as a <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"487 nanometers\"><math alttext=\"487 nanometers\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>487</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>nm</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> photon.</p>",
        "value": "i2"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No. The atom does not have a transition between levels with an energy difference equal to the energy of a <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"487 nanometers\"><math alttext=\"487 nanometers\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>487</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>nm</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> photon.</p>",
        "value": "i3"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No. The atom has only one level that is an integer multiple of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2.55 electron-volts\"><math alttext=\"2.55 electron-volts\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>2.55</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>eV</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>",
        "value": "i4"
      }
    ]
  },
